<div><strong>INFORMATION:</strong></div>
<div>Always use the disk mountpoints e.g. <strong>/mnt/disk<em><sup>[number]</sup></em><span style="color:red;">/</span></strong> when refering to disks in the array configuration, never user share or physical disk locations otherwhere on the system.</div>
<div>When planning your SnapRAID array, please do consider that it will perform best with many large files which rarely change (e.g. a media library) as opposed to many often changing small files.</div>
<div>Parity has minor overhead, so best not fill data disks to the very last byte - when using on top of Unraid parity, reasonable '<em>Minimum free space</em>' values are usually automatically set on user shares.</div>
<br>
<div>You cannot use your Unraid parity disk as SnapRAID parity disk due to SnapRAID operating on a file level as opposed to Unraid's parity operating on a block level.</div>
<div>That means in order to use SnapRAID you will need to sacrifice one regular data disk with at least the size of the largest to be protected data disk (same rules as on Unraid).</div>
<div>When using on top of Unraid parity, you will access all your protected data as you usually would through Unraid's user shares, the data of all protected disks will remain pooled as before.</div>
<br>
<details>
<summary><strong>Example Array Configuration on Unraid:</strong></summary>
<br><em><div>While SnapRAID supports a number of <a href="https://www.snapraid.it/faq#fs">various filesystems</a>, it is recommended to use it on XFS-formatted disks - which most of my testing were done on.</div>
<div>Using it on BTRFS or ZFS disks (particularly when Copy-on-Write is enabled) should be considered more experimental and may not deliver only advantages.</div>
</em>
<pre style="font-size:x-small;">
parity /mnt/disk1/snapraid.parity
content /mnt/cache/snapraid.content
content /mnt/disk2/snapraid.content
content /mnt/disk3/snapraid.content
content /mnt/disk4/snapraid.content
content /mnt/disk5/snapraid.content
data d2 /mnt/disk2/
data d3 /mnt/disk3/
data d4 /mnt/disk4/
data d5 /mnt/disk5/
</pre>
<em><div>Disk 1 is an unassigned or Unraid array data disk that is being sacrificed as SnapRAID parity disk.</div>
<div>Disk 2-5 are unassigned or Unraid array data disks with media that should be protected in the SnapRAID array.</div>
<br>
<div>The content files (which act as the file and hash catalogues) are put on e.g. the cache (for fast accessing) and also on all to be protected data disks.</div>
<div>The content files take up little space and are put on as many disks as possible (excluding the parity disks) to never be lost or corruptible during a disk failure.</div>
<br>
<div>For only partially protecting data (SnapRAID does large, rarely changing files best) like certain folders you can use include/exclude patterns (check the manual about this).</div>
<div>Advanced setups are possible for disks which are not part of Unraid's array, e.g. pooling of self-mounted SnapRAID-protected disks using tools like mergerFS is possible for expert users.</div>
</em></details><br>

